description.narrative:
General question: Results related to the intended outcome 2014Question: Summarise results related to the intended outcome (this information will be sent to Open Aid)Answer: Sweden is a long term cooperation partner in the energy sector in Tanzania and has supported the establishment of the Rural Energy Agency (REA) and the Rural Energy Fund (REF) by financing assistance in policy formulation and preparation of the required legal framework. Funding has also been provided by Sweden for Capacity Development of REA, implemented during 2009-2013 at an amount of SEK 14 million, and non-earmarked financing support to the REF 2010-2013/14 at a total amount of SEK 249 million.  

The objective of the Rural Energy Agency and Fund is to ensure increased access to modern energy services by rural communities in Mainland Tanzania in order to achieve social and economic  development. Rural energy projects have been receiving financing from REF to co-finance projects through provision of grants to buy down investment costs for project developers in rural areas. The planned outcome of the Swedish support to the REF are; 
a) Increased access and energy utilization  for productive use, 
b) Scaling up and access expansion of modern energy services to rural population in mainland Tanzania, 
c) Increased off-grid access to electricity and modern energy services in un-served rural areas through conventional and renewable energy resources and technologies.

During the period under review (4 years), the Agency continued to promote, facilitate and supervise implementation of projects in rural areas of Mainland Tanzania as a way of transforming rural livelihoods.  According to information collected by REA on villages with or without electricity in Mainland Tanzania in March 2014, it reveals that a total of 1,935 villages out of 11,110 rural villages were confirmed to have access to electricity. After completion of rural electrification projects under turnkey phase two which target a number of villages to be electrified, this figure will change drastically.  As at October 2014 total of 25,613 new customers have been connected using the financing from Rural Energy Fund from all Regions in Mainland Tanzania and number of connections from each region range from 146 to 4,247. 

The Socio-economic Impact Assessment of Rural Energy Projects in Mainland Tanzania carried out during Financial Year 2013/14 reveals that there is a clear indication in the surveyed villages that electricity displaces low-quality lighting sources such as kerosene and candles. The survey further reveals that the main use and importance of electricity in homes is for lighting which carries 85% of the home use. Rural population puts a high value on the fact that electrification has allowed the use of TVs and Radio where it carries 50% percent of the use of electricity in beneficiaries’ homes. This plays a big part in dissemination of information and communication, leisure and entertainment. Home security at night has 36.5% of electricity use to prevent theft and vandalism.  With the supply of electricity, some households which have been connected have experienced improvement in their daily life. Lighting has brought a big change in the household both economically and socially. Productive use of electricity has been emphasized to ensure that income generating activities are generated due to the availability of electricity. 

 This clearly correspond to the achievment of outcome a and b above. Also during the reporting period, REA continued to promote and facilitate application of alternative sources of energy for cooking. In addition, the Agency facilitated provision of grants to rural communities to access clean water to villages, and other grants include installation of solar PV system in villages. This correspond to the achievement of outcome c above.

 As a way to increase energy access to rural communities at affordable costs, the Agency  continued to facilitate more private sector participation. Use of low cost design standards in projects to minimize rural electrification costs.

The increased mordern energy services access resulted/ contributed to the following:
• Replacement of fossil fuel generators in health facilities especially hospitals has improved 
  services and reduced operating and maintenance costs;
• Emerging income generating activities such as milling and welding machines, salons, cell 
  phone charging centres and cold storage that has improved livelihood in the rural areas;
• Reduction of cost for grain milling after installation of electric driven motors with impact to all;
• Although the project has achieved completion targets, connection of customers is lower than 
  forecasted; mainly due to the high cost of electrification in rural areas
• Maintaining and attracting professionals (teachers, nurses, doctors etc) to work in rural areas; 
• Rural secondary schools and health facilities services are extended till night hours; students  
  have easy access to night hour reading and doing their homeworks; 
• Physical infrastructure for rural electrification has been put in place for further distribution in 
  future as needs arise;
